{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2a4f17c4-c8b7-46dc-990e-8bb7e0441393","content":"The working directory is empty and contains no repository documentation on this topic. Here's what I know:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship with `createdump` (that's a CoreCLR tool). On macOS, use the OS-native mechanisms:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — macOS disables them by default:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Run your app** — when it crashes, macOS writes a core file to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Check `/cores/`** for the dump:\n   ```bash\n   ls -la /cores/\n   ```\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is missing or empty**, ensure the directory exists and is writable:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`** (Xcode's debugger):\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **macOS Crash Reports** — Apple also writes `.ips` crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These contain stack traces and can be viewed in Console.app or a text editor.\n\n> **Tip:** On macOS 12+, `kern.corefile` controls the path. Check with `sysctl kern.corefile`. SIP (System Integrity Protection) may also prevent core dumps for some binaries.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"049a930d-2178-462e-a49d-4cedda5ee35f","outputTokens":374,"requestId":"204F:9F427:718114:845DC1:69F01236"},"id":"dfe7a805-ce14-4e9d-8cdb-b340711078c0","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:50:06.720Z","parentId":"d06a2bf5-143a-42b6-87db-41e81d32d9ce"}
